Dear University Administration,

I
am writing on behalf of an anonymous international advocacy campaign
known as **Gender Watchdog**, which is coordinating a multi-region
effort to expose and address structural gender and safety risks at
**Dongguk University**, particularly within its **graduate film
program**.

Dongguk, a Buddhist-affiliated university,
maintains active ties to the domestic and international arts sector.
However, its graduate program has exhibited long-standing structural
vulnerabilities:

- An **all-male faculty composition**,

- **No student-led gender advocacy body** (the Women’s
Council was disbanded in 2018),  

- **Lack of transparent
harassment reporting channels**,  

- A **shared academic
building with Sidus FNH**, a major production company — leading to
unsupervised contact between students and industry insiders.

These
structural conditions are not only ethically concerning but have
drawn the attention of:

- A **global university rankings
organization**,  

- Multiple **North American universities**,
now reassessing academic partnerships due to **Title IX
exposure**.

